"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388079","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-09","<p>The government is committed to seeing an improvement in the levels of provision of accessibility services for video-on-demand (VoD) services. We have been monitoring progress of the provision of access services for VoD content since 2013 through engagement with the Authority for Television On Demand (ATVOD), platform operators and content providers. We will work with them - and use information from the April 2015 paper by Action on Hearing Loss, Sense and RNIB - to define a target that we will expect providers to reach by mid-2016. If ATVOD's 2015 annual survey of VoD services indicates that significant progress has not been made then, as we stated in the Connectivity, Content and Consumers paper (July 2013), we will consider legislation in 2016.</p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-09T14:02:54.093Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388079/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388079/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388079/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-06","Video on Demand: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress he has made on setting targets for on-demand broadcasters to provide subtitles and audio description for people with sensory loss.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","900862"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388758","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-09","<p>To date 18 Local TV services have launched across the UK, increasing the range and availability of local news, information and other local programming in areas served.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-09T13:33:51.693Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388758/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388758/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388758/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-06","Local Broadcasting: Television","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what progress his Department has made on the roll out of local television services.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","900867"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388759","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-09","<p>The Minister for Sport and Tourism has already had a number of discussions with the Premier League about how best to support the game. Further meetings are planned in the weeks and months ahead, but we are agreed that football's grassroots need greater investment and we will work in partnership to ensure that this happens<em>.</em></p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-07-09T16:31:47.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388759/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388759/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388759/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-06","Football","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions he has had with the English Premier League on promoting grass roots sport.","false","Biography information for Harry Harpham","Sheffield, Brightside and Hillsborough","Harry Harpham","900868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388760","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-09","<p>The Office for National Statistics has estimated that tourism was worth £59.6 billion Gross Value Added to the UK economy in 2014. Taking account of indirect benefits, Deloitte forecast that tourism would be worth an estimated £133.6 billion last year, supporting 3.16 million jobs.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2015-07-09T16:28:56.997Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388760/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388760/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388760/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-06","Tourism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent estimate he has made of the contribution made by tourism to the economy.","false","Biography information for David Rutley","Macclesfield","David Rutley","900869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388761","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-09","<p>The creative industries continue to play a key role in our economic recovery, outperforming almost all other sectors of the economy. Figures published on 30th June showed the creative industries accounted for 1.8 million jobs in the UK in 2014, an increase of nearly 16% since 2011, with a further 900,000 creative jobs in the wider economy.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-09T13:31:49.563Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388761/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388761/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388761/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-06","Arts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent assessment he has made of the contribution of creative industries to the economy.","false","Biography information for Chris White","Warwick and Leamington","Chris White","900866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388762","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-07-09","<p>The Government recognises the important role that sport plays in all our lives and a Free-to-Air Listed Events regime has operated in the UK for many years. Taking into account the list, it is a commercial matter for the broadcasters as to what sporting events they choose to bid for and how they show them.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-07-09T13:37:52.597Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388762/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388762/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/388762/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-07-06","Broadcasting: Football","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if he will have discussions with broadcasters on free-to-view broadcasting of international football matches involving the home nations.","false","Biography information for Owen Thompson","Midlothian","Owen Thompson","900870"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387554","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-13","<p>Neither the Government nor any other UK public body have been involved in any investor-state dispute settlement claims that have either had a tribunal ruling or reached any settlement since 1997 under our entire network of bilateral and multilateral investment protection agreements.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-07-13T15:53:12.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387554/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387554/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387554/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-03","Investment: Treaties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what proportion of investor-state dispute settlements which (a) the Government and (b) another UK public body has been involved in resulted in a (i) tribunal ruling in favour of the Government or public body, (ii) ruling in favour of an investor, (iii) settlement resulting in a cash payment from the Government or another public body and (iv) settlement resulting in a change of policy, regulation or law in each year since 1997.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","5579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387555","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-13","<p>The UK is not subject to any centres for investor-state dispute settlement. However, we have included reference to a number of institutions related to international dispute resolution in our bilateral investment treaties: the Swedish Chamber of Commerce (SCC), the International Centre for the Settlement of Investment Disputes (ICSID), a part of the World Bank, and the United Nations Commission on International Trade Law (UNCITRAL). The SCC and ICSID can provide a venue and procedural rules for arbitral proceedings and UNCITRAL just provides procedural rules.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-07-13T15:52:23.693Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387555/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387555/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387555/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-03","Investment: Treaties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, which arbitration centres for investor-state dispute settlement the UK is subject to.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","5581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387556","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-13","<p>The UK is party to 94 Bilateral Investment Treaties and the Energy Charter Treaty, all of which include an investor-state dispute settlement mechanism. A list of the UK’s Bilateral Investment Treaties is available online (also including treaties terminated by South Africa and Bolivia) at <a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20130104161243/http:/www.fco.gov.uk/en/publications-and-documents/treaties/treaty-texts/ippas-investment-promotion/" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20130104161243/http://www.fco.gov.uk/en/publications-and-documents/treaties/treaty-texts/ippas-investment-promotion/</a>.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-07-13T15:51:24.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387556/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387556/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387556/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-03","Investment: Treaties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what agreements which the UK is party to include an investor-state dispute settlement system as part of that agreement.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","5582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387557","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-13","<p /> <p>The Government has been involved in one investor-state dispute settlement claim under our network of bilateral and multilateral investment protection treaties. We received notice of the claim in 2006 but the investor has not completed the procedural requirements for the claim to be heard by a tribunal. Other public bodies in the UK have never faced an investor-state dispute settlement claim.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2015-07-13T15:50:26.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387557/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387557/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387557/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-03","Investment: Treaties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, in how many investor-state dispute settlements (a) the Government and (b) other public bodies in the UK have been involved in each year since 1997.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","5580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387558","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-10","<p>No specific assessment has been made of the effect of the directly-acting EU Single Market regulation 1272/2008 (CLP) on small scale manufacturers of candles and other scented goods or on the competitive position of EU-based scented oil manufacturers. However, in 2007, the Health and Safety Executive carried out an initial regulatory impact assessment of the overall costs and benefits from the implementation of CLP.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","5444","2015-07-10T13:59:17.31Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387558/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387558/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387558/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-03","Hazardous Substances: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the effect of regulation (EC) No 1272/2008 on classification, labelling and packaging of substances and mixtures on the competitive position of EU-based scented oil manufacturers compared to US-based manufacturers.","false","Biography information for Kirsten Oswald","East Renfrewshire","Kirsten  Oswald","5600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387559","Cabinet Office","false","2015-07-08","<p>In line with long-established convention, the Government does not generally publish information relating to the proceedings of Cabinet and its committees.</p>","West Dorset","Mr Oliver Letwin",,"2015-07-08T15:32:19.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387559/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Letwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387559/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387559/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-07-03","Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, if he will place in the Library the unredacted minutes of the 15 committee meetings chaired by the then Lord Chancellor that met between May and July 1997 to discuss legislation on the devolution of power to Scotland, Wales and the English regions.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","5530"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387560","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-13","<p>The government understands the importance of the agricultural sector to the UK economy. The Government keeps all taxes under review.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","5524","2015-07-13T13:19:33.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387560/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387560/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387560/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-03","Taxation: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will review the taxation of rural land and how that taxation effects decisions to let land on farm business tenancies.","false","Biography information for Neil Parish","Tiverton and Honiton","Neil Parish","5527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387561","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-13","<p>The government understands the importance of the agricultural sector to the UK economy. The Government keeps all taxes under review.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","5527","2015-07-13T13:19:33.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387561/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387561/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387561/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-03","Inheritance Tax: Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make it his policy to limit Agricultural Property Relief from inheritance tax to encourage longer term farm business tenancies.","false","Biography information for Neil Parish","Tiverton and Honiton","Neil Parish","5524"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387562","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-13","<p>Such estimates do not exist at the current time. The commitment to restrict access to benefits for four years is intended to ensure that EU migrants make a sustained economic contribution to the UK before they can take something out. The Government is also concerned to ensure that national welfare systems do not provide an unintended additional incentive for large migratory movements. For these reasons reforming access to benefits for mobile EU nationals is one of our priorities for the renegotiation and the Prime Minister is working with his European partners to achieve this.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-07-13T13:23:33.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387562/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387562/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387562/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-03","Social Security Benefits: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of savings to the public purse of restricted access to social security for citizens of other EU countries for the first four years of their residency in each of the next three financial years; and whether such restrictions apply to (a) child benefit and (b) tax credit claims.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","5572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387563","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-13","<p>HM Treasury officials are not making proposals on the taxation of e-cigarettes to the European Commission. They are engaging in preliminary technical discussions at the EU level through the Fiscalis programme.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","5561","2015-07-13T13:21:31.22Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387563/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387563/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387563/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-03","Electronic Cigarettes: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what proposals his officials plan to make on the taxation of e-cigarettes to the European Commission's Fiscalis Programme.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","5563"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387564","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-13","<p>The requested information is available in the publication ‘Disaggregated tax and NICs receipts: statistics table’ on the GOV.UK website:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/disaggregation-of-hmrc-tax-receipts" target="_blank">gov.uk/government/statistics/disaggregation-of-hmrc-tax-receipts</a>.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>This publication provides finalised figures for each country in the UK of the total amount paid by HMRC for Child Benefit in all tax years from 2003-04 to 2013-14, and also includes provisional figures for 2014-15 which are subject to change.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The relevant Child Benefit figures can be found in last column of the publication.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2015-07-13T13:24:35.163Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387564/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387564/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387564/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-03","Child Benefit: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much has been spent on child benefit in Northern Ireland in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","5567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387565","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-07-13","<p>Trade unions have a constructive role to play in maintaining positive industrial relations. The British Social Attitudes Survey and the Workplace Employment Relations Survey provide information on how the population, employers and union members view the services and activities of Trade Unions. The Office for National Statistics publishes estimates of the approximate Gross Added Value for Trade Union activities as well as the number of disputes (and days lost to industrial action).</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-07-13T11:55:34.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387565/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387565/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387565/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-07-03","Trade Unions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the contribution of trades unions to the UK economy.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","5578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387566","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-07","<p>The Government will introduce a new residency requirement, so that EU migrants cannot be considered for social housing unless they have been living here for at least four years; and made clear that this would be taken forward as part of wider EU treaty negotiation on welfare changes.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","5576","2015-07-07T14:25:06.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387566/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387566/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387566/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-03","Social Rented Housing: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his policy is on requiring social housing providers to verify the length of residency of citizens from other EU countries.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","5575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387567","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-07","<p>The Government will introduce a new residency requirement, so that EU migrants cannot be considered for social housing unless they have been living here for at least four years; and made clear that this would be taken forward as part of wider EU treaty negotiation on welfare changes.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","5575","2015-07-07T14:25:06.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387567/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387567/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387567/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-03","Social Rented Housing: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how he intends to prohibit (a) social housing providers and (b) housing associations from accepting as residents citizens from other EU countries who do not meet the criteria of a four-year residency before accessing social housing.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","5576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387568","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-13","<p>English Housing Survey data shows that in 2012-13 there were 129,000 households living in social housing in England with a household reference person whose nationality was an EU country other than UK. This represents 15% of all households in England with a household reference person whose nationality was an EU country other than UK.</p><p>Information on the proportion of the total affordable housing stock in England which is leased to citizens of other EU countries is not held centrally.<br><br>Housing in Scotland, Wales or Northen Ireland is a matter for the devolved adminstrations.<br><br></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","5584","2015-07-13T14:21:01.17Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387568/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387568/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387568/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-03","Social Rented Housing: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many citizens of other EU countries live in social housing in (a) Scotland, (b) Wales, (c) Northern Ireland and (d) England; and what proportion of all citizens of other EU countries resident in each constituent part of the UK are so housed.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","5573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387569","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-09","<p>As the my rt.hon. Friend, the Secretary of State for Transport (Patrick McLoughlin) explained to the House in a statement on 25 June 2015, <em>Official Report</em>, Column 1067-1070, the electrification of the Transpennine route east of Stalybridge will be paused in order to ensure the programme overall delivers the maximum benefits and value to passengers. He reported to the Transport Committee in March 2015 that Transpennine electrification would be delayed to the 2020s and subsequently confirmed that the programme has been paused. It is right that my rt. hon. Friend has asked Network Rail to undertake a re-plan, and our Departments are in regular dialogue about such matters.</p><p> </p><p>Already, 32 miles of track from Liverpool to Manchester has been electrified, with the first electric service running earlier this year, replacing 2-car diesel trains with 4-car electric trains. The new Northern and Transpennine franchises starting next year will increase overall capacity by 36% by the end of 2019 and provide an extra 200 services each weekday, irrespective of when electrification east of Stalybridge is completed.</p><p> </p><p>I am therefore confident that the area will still benefit enormously from the investments being made.</p><p> </p><p>The Northern Powerhouse is not purely a transport vision; it is an ambition to turn around decades of underperformance in the North, with commitments to science and technology, digital and innovation, culture and tourism, across the region, alongside devolving power to the major cities to give the North a powerful new voice.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","5571 ; 5687","2015-07-09T14:56:59.34Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387569/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387569/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387569/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-03","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment his Department has made of the effect on regional devolution and economic development of the decision to pause the electrification of the TransPennine rail route between Leeds and Manchester.","false","Biography information for Jo Cox","Batley and Spen","Jo Cox","5570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387570","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-13","<p>There are no plans to change the planning appeal system to enable central government intervention after a decision on an appeal has been taken. The current system allows for any planning appeal to be recovered from the Planning Inspectorate for determination by the Secretary of State at any point up to publication of the appeal decision. Once the decision has been published, aggrieved parties can seek to legally challenge it within prescribed timescales.</p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-07-13T15:29:22.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387570/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387570/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387570/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-03","Planning Permission: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will take steps to call in those planning applications for further consideration which have been initially rejected but allowed on appeal.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","5542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387571","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-13","<p>Neighbourhood planning, introduced in the 2011 Localism Act, gives local people a stronger role in shaping the areas in which they live and work. For the first time community groups can produce plans that have real statutory weight in the planning system. They are able to choose where they want new homes, shops and offices to be built, have their say on what those new buildings should look like and what infrastructure should be provided, and grant planning permission for the new buildings they want to see go ahead. To date, over 1,500 local areas have been designated for neighbourhood planning, with 74 successful referendums and 62 plans and orders brought into force.</p><p> </p><p>The Government announced in the Queen’s Speech that the Housing Bill would include measures to simplify and speed up the neighbourhood planning system, to support communities that seek to meet local housing and other development needs through neighbourhood planning. We have also launched a £22.5 million support programme for 2015 – 2018, providing grants and technical assistance to neighbourhood planning groups, and published a suite of resources to make it easier and quicker for communities to progress their plans.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-07-13T15:31:01.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387571/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387571/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387571/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-03","Planning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure that local residents have more of a say over planning decisions in their area.","false","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","5543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387572","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-13","<p>English Housing Survey data shows that in 2012-13 there were 129,000 households living in social housing in England with a household reference person whose nationality was an EU country other than UK. This represents 15% of all households in England with a household reference person whose nationality was an EU country other than UK.</p><p>Information on the proportion of the total affordable housing stock in England which is leased to citizens of other EU countries is not held centrally.<br><br>Housing in Scotland, Wales or Northen Ireland is a matter for the devolved adminstrations.<br><br></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","5573","2015-07-13T14:21:01.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387572/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387572/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387572/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-07-03","Social Rented Housing: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of the total affordable housing stock in (a) Scotland, (b) Wales, (c) Northern Ireland and (d) England is leased to citizens of other EU countries.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","5584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387573","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-07-09","<p>As the my rt.hon. Friend, the Secretary of State for Transport (Patrick McLoughlin) explained to the House in a statement on 25 June 2015, <em>Official Report</em>, Column 1067-1070, the electrification of the Transpennine route east of Stalybridge will be paused in order to ensure the programme overall delivers the maximum benefits and value to passengers. He reported to the Transport Committee in March 2015 that Transpennine electrification would be delayed to the 2020s and subsequently confirmed that the programme has been paused. It is right that my rt. hon. Friend has asked Network Rail to undertake a re-plan, and our Departments are in regular dialogue about such matters.</p><p> </p><p>Already, 32 miles of track from Liverpool to Manchester has been electrified, with the first electric service running earlier this year, replacing 2-car diesel trains with 4-car electric trains. The new Northern and Transpennine franchises starting next year will increase overall capacity by 36% by the end of 2019 and provide an extra 200 services each weekday, irrespective of when electrification east of Stalybridge is completed.</p><p> </p><p>I am therefore confident that the area will still benefit enormously from the investments being made.</p><p> </p><p>The Northern Powerhouse is not purely a transport vision; it is an ambition to turn around decades of underperformance in the North, with commitments to science and technology, digital and innovation, culture and tourism, across the region, alongside devolving power to the major cities to give the North a powerful new voice.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton","5570 ; 5687","2015-07-09T14:56:59.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387573/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387573/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387573/answer",,,,,"7