"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387605","Department of Health","false","2015-07-08","<p>No such guidance has been given to NHS England, which is an independent organisation and is responsible for deciding how its commissioning decisions should be communicated to patients and their families.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence does not make decisions on which treatments are commissioned by the National Health Service.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-07-08T13:18:50.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387605/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387605/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387605/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-03","Clinical Trials: Families","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidance his Department gives to NHS England and NICE on communicating treatment commissioning decisions to families of patients on clinical trials before such decisions are officially announced.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","5592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387606","Department of Health","false","2015-07-08","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence is an independent organisation and is responsible for developing its own methodology for the evaluation of drugs and treatments through its highly specialised technologies programme.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","5594","2015-07-08T13:30:25.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387606/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387606/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387606/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-03","Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidance his Department gives to NICE on the amount of time it gives to stakeholders to provide additional evidence for a highly specialised technology appraisal after it has issued interim guidance on that appraisal.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","5593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387607","Department of Health","false","2015-07-08","<p>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence is an independent organisation and is responsible for developing its own methodology for the evaluation of drugs and treatments through its highly specialised technologies programme.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","5593","2015-07-08T13:30:25.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387607/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387607/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387607/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-03","Medical Treatments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what guidance is given to NICE on the amount of time it takes to conduct a highly specialised technology appraisal.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","5594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387608","Department of Health","false","2015-07-08","<p>A patient may be referred to an NHS service which is geographically located in Scotland.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Clinical commissioning groups (CCGs) are responsible for commissioning the majority of NHS services. It is for CCGs to commission services to meet the needs of their local population.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>CCGs are free to commission services in Scotland as long as such services comply with the NHS Constitution, which sets out rights for patients, public and staff. It outlines NHS commitments to patients and staff, and the responsibilities that the public, patients and staff owe to one another to ensure that the NHS operates fairly and effectively.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>NHS England has published the document <em>‘Who Pays? Determining responsibility for payments to providers’</em> which provides guidance for CCGs on commissioning services from hospitals in Scotland and outside their own area.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A copy has been attached.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-07-08T13:25:57.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387608/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387608/answer","Who Pays.pdf","Who Pays.pdf","NHS England 'Who Pays?' August 2013","NHS England 'Who Pays?' August 2013","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387608/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-03","Out of Area Treatment: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what his Department's policy is on cross-border patient referrals to Scotland.","false","Biography information for Anne-Marie Trevelyan","Berwick-upon-Tweed","Mrs Anne-Marie Trevelyan","5587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387609","Department of Health","false","2015-07-13","<p>Grants made under Section 64 of the Health Services and Public Health Act 1968 can be made in a number of ways. The Voluntary Sector Investment Fund grant schemes such as the Strategic Partner Programme; Innovation, Excellence and Strategic Development Fund; and Health and Social Care Volunteering Fund involve a competitive process. Some non-competed grants are also made by the Department using Section 64 powers. Any voluntary sector organisations can submit a proposal for such a grant and all applications are assessed against the same criteria.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The assessment includes a requirement for officials to consider whether there are other suppliers who can provide the requirements before awarding a grant to an organisation making an ad-hoc request. A formal assessment of the application for grant funding from Action on Smoking and Health (ASH) for the 2015-16 financial year has not yet been completed. Last year, the assessment of the application for 2014-15 funding concluded that ASH was the only charity in this area with the appropriate national reach and focus, and appropriate standing in the international arena.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","5547","2015-07-13T13:55:10.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387609/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387609/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387609/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-03","Action on Smoking and Health: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 24 June 2015 to Question 2761 on smoking and health: finance, whether the award of such a grant is made on a competitive and transparent basis.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","5566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387610","Department of Health","false","2015-07-13","<p>Grants made under Section 64 of the Health Services and Public Health Act 1968 can be made in a number of ways. The Voluntary Sector Investment Fund grant schemes such as the Strategic Partner Programme; Innovation, Excellence and Strategic Development Fund; and Health and Social Care Volunteering Fund involve a competitive process. Some non-competed grants are also made by the Department using Section 64 powers. Any voluntary sector organisations can submit a proposal for such a grant and all applications are assessed against the same criteria.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The assessment includes a requirement for officials to consider whether there are other suppliers who can provide the requirements before awarding a grant to an organisation making an ad-hoc request. A formal assessment of the application for grant funding from Action on Smoking and Health (ASH) for the 2015-16 financial year has not yet been completed. Last year, the assessment of the application for 2014-15 funding concluded that ASH was the only charity in this area with the appropriate national reach and focus, and appropriate standing in the international arena.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","5566","2015-07-13T13:55:10.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387610/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387610/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387610/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-03","Action on Smoking and Health: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 24 June 2015 to Question 2761, what assessment he has made of whether organisations or groups other than Action on Smoking and Health (ASH) are capable to deliver the services for which ASH has applied for grant funding.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","5547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387611","Department of Health","false","2015-07-13","<p>Grants to Action on Smoking and Health (ASH) have been awarded under Section 64 of the Health Services and Public Health Act 1968. All grants awarded under this legislative power must be approved by both HM Treasury and either the Secretary of State for Health or another Health Minister. Recommendations to Ministers for funding are only made once an assessment of the proposal has been made by officials against standard business case criteria which include a Strategic Case, Economic Case, Financial Case, Commercial Case and Project Governance.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-07-13T14:26:12.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387611/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387611/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387611/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-03","Action on Smoking and Health: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 24 June 2015 to Question 2761 on smoking and health: finance, what the job title is of the official who will decide whether such a grant is awarded; and what criteria that official will apply in reaching that decision.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","5548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387612","Department of Health","false","2015-07-13","<p>We have reviewed the Department’s records and have identified that the Department received a Freedom of Information (FOI) Request in May 2014 related to a grant made to the Action on Smoking and Health which was followed up by a further FOI request in June 2014.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-07-13T14:25:07.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387612/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387612/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387612/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-03","Department of Health: Lobbying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 24 June 2015 to Question 2691, whether his Department has received representations on the use of grant funding provided to outside groups being used for the lobbying of his Department.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","5554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387613","Department of Health","false","2015-07-09","<p>As is normal practice, the United Kingdom’s responses to European Commission proposals are cleared across Government. The Department will respond to any request from HM Treasury to agree the Government’s line on this subject if and when firm proposals are made by the Commission.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-07-09T15:16:37.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387613/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387613/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387613/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-07-03","Electronic Cigarettes: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what contribution his Department is making to Government proposals on the taxation of e-cigarettes being made to the European Commission's Fiscalis Programme.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","5562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387614","HM Treasury","false","2015-07-13","<p>HM Treasury officials are not making proposals on the taxation of e-cigarettes to the European Commission. They are engaging in preliminary technical discussions at the EU level through the Fiscalis programme.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","5563","2015-07-13T13:21:31.327Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387614/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387614/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-07-03","Electronic Cigarettes: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what contribution his Department is making to Government proposals on the taxation of e-cigarettes being made to the European Commission's Fiscalis Programme.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","5561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387615","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-07-08","<p>It is the longstanding policy of successive British governments not to comment on intelligence matters. I refer my hon. Friend to the judgment of the Investigatory Powers Tribunal, 22 June 2015, as corrected on 1 July 2015, which found that any interception that occurred was lawful and proportionate under the Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act (RIPA) 2000.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2015-07-08T13:13:25.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387615/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387615/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-07-03","Amnesty International: Surveillance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Investigatory Powers Tribunal Determination of 22 June 2015, IPT/13/194/H, and subsequent correction of 1 July 2015, under what statutory provision the interception of the communications of Amnesty International by GCHQ was authorised.","false","Biography information for Mr David Davis","Haltemprice and Howden","Mr David Davis","5586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387616","Home Office","false","2015-07-07","<p>To protect young people and others from exposure to potentially dangerous substances, the Psychoactive Substances Bill provides for a blanket ban on the supply of psychoactive substances.</p><p>The Bill captures substances supplied for human consumption for their psychoactive effects. Schedule 1 to the Bill contains a wide list of exemptions, developed in conjunction with other government departments, capturing substances already controlled by existing regulation such as food, alcohol, caffeine, tobacco and medicines.</p><p>Further substances can be exempted following consultation between the Secretary of State, the Advisory Council for the Misuse of Drugs and other consultees as considered appropriate.</p><p>The Government does not support a regime which allows for the regulated sale of so called ‘low harm’ psychoactive substances and the regulation-making power in clause 3 is not designed for such a purpose (as evidenced by the absence of any associated provisions in the Bill to regulate the sale of approved ‘low harm’ psychoactive substances).</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-07-07T15:54:36.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387616/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387616/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387616/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-03","Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what criteria she plans to apply to determine which psychoactive substances are not covered by the proposed psychoactive substances ban.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","5601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387617","Home Office","false","2015-07-13","<p>As the Investigatory Powers Tribunal (IPT) said in its judgment of 22 June 2015, any interception that occurred in this case was lawful, necessary and proportionate.</p><p>While the IPT has found in favour of two Non-Governmental Organisations (NGOs), it has made clear that neither of the NGOs suffered material detriment, damage or prejudice as a result of the breaches.</p><p>Caution should be exercised against drawing conclusions from the IPT’s ruling about the target of any such interception that may have taken place. However I can neither confirm nor deny specifics relating to this or any other case.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2015-07-13T10:07:54.933Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387617/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387617/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387617/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-03","Amnesty International: Surveillance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the implications for her policies of the ruling by the Investigatory Powers Tribunal IPT/13/194/CH, that Amnesty International has been subjected to unlawful surveillance by the Government; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","5602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387618","Home Office","false","2015-07-09","<p>As a condition of sponsoring a worker under Tier 2, sponsoring employers are required to monitor the immigration status of their workers.</p><p>To ensure sponsors are aware of changes to Immigration Rules, UK Visas &amp; Immigration regularly sends online notifications to sponsors, and the appropriate guidance documents are updated to reflect changes to the Immigration Rules. UK Visas &amp; Immigration also operates a Business Helpdesk to support sponsors with any enquiries.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2015-07-09T14:45:40.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387618/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387618/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387618/answer","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387618/answer/previousversion/12964","Biography information for James Brokenshire","1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-07-03","Immigration Controls: Migrant Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to her Answer of 2 July 2015 to Question 4295, if she will make it her policy to ensure that current employers of workers on tier 2 visas whose immigration status is changing as a result of 2011 immigration rules changes requiring workers who have been in the UK for more five years to earn more than £35,000 gross per annum are aware that these changes are now taking effect; and if she will provide support to such employers to identify employees whose immigration status may now change.","false","Biography information for Kirsty Blackman","Aberdeen North","Kirsty Blackman","5551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387619","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-09","<p>The MDGs have been an enormous success, helping to focus global attention on poverty and resulting in, for example, extreme poverty being halved, maternal deaths falling by 45% and the under-five deaths dropping from 12m a year to 6m a year.</p><p> </p><p>The UK has made a significant contribution to these successes. For example, the UK has supported over 43 million people to access water, sanitation or hygiene interventions; and over 19 million children under 5 and pregnant women to access nutrition programmes. The UK’s binding commitment to 0.7% of GNI for official development assistance is solid evidence of the UK’s leadership on international development.</p><p> </p><p>The UK continues to make a strong contribution to the ongoing negotiations in the United Nations to agree the post-2015 Development Agenda in advance of the post-2015 summit in September of this year, building on the Prime Minister’s co-chairing of the High Level Panel. The UK will play its full part in delivering the post-2015 agenda when it is launched in January 2016.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening","5555","2015-07-09T16:21:33.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387619/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387619/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-03","International Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the UK's contribution to the performance of the UN's Millenium Development Goals.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","5583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387620","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-09","<p>The MDGs have been an enormous success, helping to focus global attention on poverty and resulting in, for example, extreme poverty being halved, maternal deaths falling by 45% and the under-five deaths dropping from 12m a year to 6m a year.</p><p> </p><p>The UK has made a significant contribution to these successes. For example, the UK has supported over 43 million people to access water, sanitation or hygiene interventions; and over 19 million children under 5 and pregnant women to access nutrition programmes. The UK’s binding commitment to 0.7% of GNI for official development assistance is solid evidence of the UK’s leadership on international development.</p><p> </p><p>The UK continues to make a strong contribution to the ongoing negotiations in the United Nations to agree the post-2015 Development Agenda in advance of the post-2015 summit in September of this year, building on the Prime Minister’s co-chairing of the High Level Panel. The UK will play its full part in delivering the post-2015 agenda when it is launched in January 2016.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Putney","Justine Greening","5583","2015-07-09T16:21:33.023Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387620/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387620/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387620/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-03","Developing Countries: Sustainable Development","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps she plans to take to ensure that the UK makes a contribution to the post-2015 UN agenda on the Millennium Development Goals.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","5555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387621","Department for International Development","false","2015-07-09","<p>As Secretary of State for International Development, I champion this issue every day as part of my broader plan to improve the prospects of women and girls overseas. I am proud of the impact my department has achieved in tackling violence against women and girls, not least through the 2014 Girl Summit which focussed on eradicating Female Genital Mutilation and Early and Forced Child Marriage.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2015-07-09T16:20:20.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387621/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387621/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387621/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2015-07-03","Developing Countries: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what discussions she has had with Ministerial colleagues on re-establishing the position of Ministerial Champion for Tackling Violence against Women and Girls Overseas.","false","Biography information for Mr Alistair Carmichael","Orkney and Shetland","Mr Alistair Carmichael","5568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387622","Prime Minister","false","2015-07-09","<p>I refer the right hon. Member to the answer given to the hon. Member for Brighton, Pavilion (Ms Lucas) by the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, my hon. Friend the Member for Bournemouth East (Mr Ellwood) on 29 June 2015, UIN 4073.</p>","Witney","Mr David Cameron",,"2015-07-09T15:58:08.473Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387622/answer","Biography information for Mr David Cameron","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387622/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387622/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2015-07-03","Egypt: Diplomatic Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, when he next plans to meet the President of Egypt.","false","Biography information for Ann Clwyd","Cynon Valley","Ann Clwyd","5577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387623","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-08","<p>The Government is currently assessing whether the 19 routes that submitted applications for start-up aid funding meet the European Commission guidelines and will announce then after the Budget how we will take this forward.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2015-07-08T12:00:07.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387623/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387623/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387623/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-03","Aviation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, with reference to Start-up aid for airports: applications received, published by his Department on 27 March 2015, for what reason he has not yet published a short-list of routes that have successfully met the criteria at initial application stage; when he intends to publish that short-list and (c) when he intends to announce successful bids.","false","Biography information for Catherine McKinnell","Newcastle upon Tyne North","Catherine McKinnell","5552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387624","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-10","<p>In March of this year the department signed a formal partnership agreement with Rail North, representing 29 local transport authorities. This will govern the new Northern and TransPennine Express (TPE) franchises from April 2016. The agreement includes important mechanisms to enable the Rail North authorities to make decisions on changes to their local rail services and make investments in these franchises to make improvements.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>It also enables further devolution to take place during the life of the franchises.　 Under the agreement, the Department for Transport will work together with Rail North, through a single joint strategic board and management team based in Leeds, to manage and develop these 2 new franchises once they are let. A core team of 5 headed by a managing director will be in place at the end of year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Rail North has already been actively involved in the design of the future Northern and TPE franchises and the Partnership Agreement is a significant step towards full devolution of rail services. The franchise specification took into account the uncertainty in delivery of Transpennine electrification.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-07-10T13:32:18.07Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387624/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387624/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387624/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-03","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what opportunities his Department gave local authorities to make representations to it before the decision was made to pause the electrification of the TransPennine rail route between Leeds and Manchester.","false","Biography information for Jo Cox","Batley and Spen","Jo Cox","5564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387625","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-10","<p>The Secretary of State regularly meets Network Rail to discuss a wide range of topics.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-07-10T13:35:27.29Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387625/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387625/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387625/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-03","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, on which occasions he met Network Rail to discuss the electrification of the TransPennine rail route between Leeds and Manchester; and when he received updates from Network Rail on that project.","false","Biography information for Jo Cox","Batley and Spen","Jo Cox","5565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387626","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-10","<p>The Government has ambitious plans for rail which is why Network Rail has been allocated a record £38 billion for the period from 2014-2019. It is for Network Rail to determine precisely how much will be allocated to the rail investment programme in the North of England but the Secretary of State expects that the committed programme set out in the High Level Output Specification ([Rail Investment Strategy]) will be delivered.　 The government’s enhancements programme is an ambitious and stretching programme and it needs to be re-planned to ensure it remains deliverable and affordable, which is the task that has been asked of Sir Peter Hendy.</p><p> </p><p>However, the franchising programme will continue to deliver for passengers and taxpayers as planned and live procurements, including Northern and Transpennine Express, which will transform rail services across the region with more service, capacity and the scrapping of Pacers, will not be affected.　 Other rail investments in the north also continue to be delivered; for example the electrification of the lines between Liverpool and Manchester and Liverpool and Wigan has already been completed and there will be the roll-out of state of the art Intercity Express trains on the East Coast route during this Parliament.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Transpennine electrification　remains a major part of our economic plan for the region, but it is vital that　Network Rail gets this right.　 The Secretary of State has already explained to MPs (Transport Select Committee evidence March 2015), this means the　project will not be completed by 2019, as originally proposed. However, compromising on the　scope of this project would not be in passengers’ best interests. That is why　we continue to work with Network Rail on revised plans so that it delivers the　best possible results.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-07-10T13:24:51.993Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387626/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387626/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387626/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-03","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much has been allocated from the public purse for the rail investment programme in the North of England; and what the priorities for that programme are.","false","Biography information for Jo Cox","Batley and Spen","Jo Cox","5556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387627","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-10","<p>The timetable for electrification of the　TransPennine line east of Stalybridge will be outlined in Sir Peter Hendy's re-planning proposals this autumn.　 Transpennine electrification remains a major part of our economic plan for the region, but it is vital that Network Rail gets this right.　As the Transport Secretary has already explained to MPs (Transport Select Committee evidence March 2015), this means the project will not be completed by 2019, as originally proposed. However, compromising on the scope of this project would not be in passengers’ best interests. That is why we continue to work with Network Rail on revised plans so that it delivers the best possible results.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-07-10T13:28:47.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387627/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387627/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387627/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-03","Railways: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the timetable is for the electrification of the TransPennine rail route between Leeds and Manchester.","false","Biography information for Jo Cox","Batley and Spen","Jo Cox","5558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387628","Department for Transport","false","2015-07-08","<p>In its comprehensive review of taxi and private hire legislation, the Law Commission addressed the issue of creating a statutory definition of plying for hire. The Government is currently considering the Law Commission’s report and in line with the protocol that exists between the Government and the Law Commission, we will provide a full response in due course.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2015-07-08T12:03:06.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387628/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387628/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387628/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-07-03","Taxis","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will bring forward legislation to amend the definition of plying for hire in the taxi industry.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","5604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387629","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-13","<p>The Work Capability Assessment (WCA) was introduced by the last Labour government in October 2008 and was developed in consultation with medical and other experts, including representative groups to ensure it is appropriate for all conditions.</p><p> </p><p>Entitlement to benefit does not depend on the condition itself, the underlying cause or how it is classified, but on the disabling effects of the condition(s) present.</p><p> </p><p>When assessing a claimant, Healthcare Professionals are expected to be mindful of the fact that many illnesses produce symptoms that vary in intensity over time, and are instructed not to base their opinion solely on the situation as observed at the assessment.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-07-13T14:20:20.923Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387629/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387629/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387629/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-03","Social Security Benefits: Epilepsy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how epilepsy is taken into account in (a) work capability assessments, (b) entitlement to benefits and (c) assessments for availability for work for people with that condition.","false","Biography information for Huw Irranca-Davies","Ogmore","Huw Irranca-Davies","5528"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387630","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2015-07-09","<p /> <p>Waiting days will only be served at the beginning of a completely new claim to Universal Credit, which means people moving from low-income work are less likely to be affected.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2015-07-09T10:46:08.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387630/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387630/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387630/answer","Witham","Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/387630/answer/previousversion/13044","Biography information for Priti Patel","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-07-03","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to paragraph 12 of the report of the Social Security Advisory Committee on The Universal Credit (Waiting Days) (Amendment) Regulations 2015 (S.I. 2015 No. 1362), published June 2015, what the evidential basis is for the statement that the policy is focused on those coming to Universal Credit from relatively higher-income employment.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","5591"
